00:20:20.780 --> 00:20:24.000
The University of Cincinnati has
a history of Apple at our college.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:29.310
The history begins in 1999 when
we were unable to keep up with the

00:20:29.370 --> 00:20:31.960
pace of technology and we couldn't
afford to maintain all the labs,

00:20:31.980 --> 00:20:35.190
so we asked our students to bring
their own personal computers,

00:20:35.190 --> 00:20:36.480
which they did.

00:20:36.580 --> 00:20:40.360
They brought every variety of,
so you can imagine, Gateway, Heathkit,

00:20:40.360 --> 00:20:40.980
and so on.

00:20:41.260 --> 00:20:44.840
Only four students in our program in
architecture chose to bring an Apple.

00:20:45.490 --> 00:20:49.860
Huge monitors sitting on
these drafting tables made it

00:20:49.860 --> 00:20:50.020
impossible to build a computer.

00:20:50.020 --> 00:20:53.420
It was impossible to build conventional
study models or do large drawings.

00:20:53.420 --> 00:20:57.770
And then furthermore, the studio faculty,
of which I was one,

00:20:57.770 --> 00:21:01.470
were spending all of our time
solving IT and network issues

00:21:01.800 --> 00:21:03.880
and no time teaching design.

00:21:03.980 --> 00:21:07.390
Well, I marched right into the
chair's office and said,

00:21:07.460 --> 00:21:10.680
"We're either going to drop computers
from the curriculum or we're going

00:21:10.680 --> 00:21:13.640
to move to a laptop environment,
and we're going to do it

00:21:13.640 --> 00:21:16.560
with one platform only."
It was a hard sell at first,

00:21:16.560 --> 00:21:19.260
but as I made the argument,
they seemed to go along.

00:21:19.260 --> 00:21:23.180
Architecture, graphic,
and digital design all went that way,

00:21:23.180 --> 00:21:27.260
and that was a good chunk of our
student population in the college.

00:21:27.260 --> 00:21:31.170
And all first-year students in
those programs came with PowerBooks.

00:21:31.190 --> 00:21:35.170
The others in the college
came with other stuff.

00:21:35.340 --> 00:21:37.000
The argument was pretty easy to make.

00:21:37.140 --> 00:21:38.500
They're minimal IT.

00:21:38.640 --> 00:21:40.540
We didn't want to invest
in IT in the school.

00:21:40.540 --> 00:21:42.040
We'd rather have another faculty member.

00:21:42.040 --> 00:21:44.690
They were very intuitive
and very powerful and

00:21:44.690 --> 00:21:46.840
graphically interesting to use.

00:21:46.840 --> 00:21:49.660
And moreover, they were well-designed.

00:21:49.660 --> 00:21:52.860
If we're a college of design and we're
interested and curious about design,

00:21:52.860 --> 00:21:55.200
we ought to be using
well-designed products as well.

00:21:55.200 --> 00:21:56.800
Practice what you preach, in other words.

00:21:57.580 --> 00:22:01.270
The first wave of this laptop tsunami,
of all of these laptops

00:22:01.270 --> 00:22:03.840
arriving on our doorstep,
forced us to change some

00:22:03.920 --> 00:22:05.580
things critically right away.

00:22:05.580 --> 00:22:09.460
The administrative structure
just wasn't working.

00:22:09.460 --> 00:22:13.430
We had these silos with individuals
reporting to other individuals,

00:22:13.430 --> 00:22:16.020
and when somebody in
their area wasn't working,

00:22:16.020 --> 00:22:17.260
they were picking their nose.

00:22:17.260 --> 00:22:19.970
We immediately moved to
a horizontal structure,

00:22:19.970 --> 00:22:22.740
made it more team-like,
and fit a little bit better

00:22:22.740 --> 00:22:24.180
with the academic model.

00:22:24.310 --> 00:22:27.380
Physically, we were able to reduce
our labs one per year.

00:22:27.380 --> 00:22:34.380
We moved from six mediocre
labs to three high-end labs.

00:22:34.380 --> 00:22:37.260
The third one I didn't show a picture
of because it's the other one.

00:22:37.260 --> 00:22:41.710
So these are two of our high-end labs.

00:22:41.760 --> 00:22:46.100
The other thing that's interesting
with this many laptops in the

00:22:46.100 --> 00:22:49.440
building is any classroom is
by default now a computer lab.

00:22:49.440 --> 00:22:52.070
The students all have really
pretty good computers,

00:22:52.070 --> 00:22:57.180
and wherever we are,
we can make this a lab.

00:22:57.180 --> 00:23:01.020
We teach a lot of classes that way.

00:23:01.020 --> 00:23:02.870
In architecture,
it allowed us to get smaller

00:23:02.870 --> 00:23:05.860
desks because no longer are
they doing these huge drawings.

00:23:05.860 --> 00:23:09.420
They're doing all of their stuff in
Photoshop or Illustrator on their

00:23:09.420 --> 00:23:13.860
small laptops and printing out really
huge plots and pinning those up.

00:23:13.860 --> 00:23:17.730
So we could get by with smaller desks,
increase enrollment, more revenue.

00:23:17.760 --> 00:23:17.860
Yay.

