00:30:18.360 --> 00:30:24.650
So, let's go over the production process
of making a South Park episode.

00:30:25.710 --> 00:30:31.360
South Park began as a cardboard cutout,
stop motion animated short that then

00:30:31.360 --> 00:30:34.080
was decided to make a TV series out of.

00:30:34.100 --> 00:30:38.240
But the pilot for that TV series took
over two and a half months to develop.

00:30:38.250 --> 00:30:40.660
Obviously they couldn't do 13
episodes a year at that scale,

00:30:40.770 --> 00:30:42.910
so they had to use computers.

00:30:42.990 --> 00:30:47.840
So we developed over the course
of nine years now a production

00:30:47.840 --> 00:30:53.750
process that is very streamlined,
very organized, and very, very fast.

00:30:54.170 --> 00:30:56.440
First stage, the script.

00:30:56.440 --> 00:30:59.110
Most animated series,
or most TV series in general,

00:30:59.180 --> 00:31:01.300
start with a full script
before they do anything.

00:31:01.380 --> 00:31:02.970
We get a few pages.

00:31:03.240 --> 00:31:08.490
We get those few pages
Thursday before the Wednesday it airs.

00:31:09.180 --> 00:31:11.060
And we get a few more
pages every day after that,

00:31:11.160 --> 00:31:14.980
so we literally don't know what's
going to happen from day to day.

00:31:15.120 --> 00:31:19.780
Not until Tuesday around 9 or 10 when
we get the final pages of script.

00:31:21.160 --> 00:31:23.730
After we get that script,
we begin the storyboard process.

00:31:23.730 --> 00:31:27.100
And that's where we take those texts and
we actually convert them into images.

00:31:27.160 --> 00:31:31.180
We'll do a comic book version of the
episode to see how things looked,

00:31:31.260 --> 00:31:32.240
how things are staged.

00:31:32.240 --> 00:31:34.100
This is also where we
design our characters,

00:31:34.100 --> 00:31:37.100
our backgrounds, and color design.

00:31:37.150 --> 00:31:39.210
While that's going on,
Matt and Trey will go into

00:31:39.210 --> 00:31:41.860
the audio booth and record
all the dialogue for the show.

00:31:41.920 --> 00:31:43.850
They even do the females
because you never know if

00:31:43.940 --> 00:31:46.750
the audio is going to change,
so we don't bring our females

00:31:46.750 --> 00:31:48.490
in until the very last minute.

00:31:48.920 --> 00:31:51.670
Once those two stages are done,
we begin the animatic stage.

00:31:51.680 --> 00:31:54.080
And that's where we take the
audio and those individual frames

00:31:54.080 --> 00:31:58.270
of the storyboard and time out
the still frames to the audio.

00:31:58.590 --> 00:32:01.450
This gives the mat and tray a chance
to see how things are flowing.

00:32:01.750 --> 00:32:05.600
It also gives us a chance to see how
long each shot needs to be for animation.

00:32:05.600 --> 00:32:08.260
While the animatic stage is going on,
we have the setup stage.

00:32:08.590 --> 00:32:12.320
That's where we take those character
designs and background designs

00:32:12.400 --> 00:32:14.640
and locations and model them.

00:32:14.760 --> 00:32:18.230
We get them rigged, get them going,
getting prepared for animation.

00:32:18.490 --> 00:32:20.650
After that's done, we go to lip sync.

00:32:21.080 --> 00:32:22.800
Lip sync is the thankless job.

00:32:22.800 --> 00:32:25.320
This is the one job where they sit there,
listen to the audio,

00:32:25.370 --> 00:32:26.590
and animate just the mouths.

00:32:26.760 --> 00:32:28.000
That's all they do.

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:31.020
It's a thankless task,
but we're very dedicated to it.

00:32:31.110 --> 00:32:34.560
After all of that is done,
we can finally get to animation,

00:32:34.560 --> 00:32:36.920
where a shot spends most of its time.

00:32:37.090 --> 00:32:38.390
This is where they'll do everything else.

00:32:38.460 --> 00:32:41.000
The bobbing heads, the blinking eyes,
the dancing, the talking,

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:43.100
everything else is done there.

00:32:43.200 --> 00:32:47.190
And this basically is the primary
part of the iterative process where

00:32:47.300 --> 00:32:50.640
we'll do a first pass at a shot,
send it through the pipeline,

00:32:50.640 --> 00:32:52.840
Trey will look at it if he likes it,
great,

00:32:52.840 --> 00:32:54.850
if he doesn't he goes back through.

00:32:55.570 --> 00:32:58.610
Our render queue has evolved over
the years to the point that it's a

00:32:58.690 --> 00:33:01.410
completely automated process now.

00:33:01.520 --> 00:33:03.880
The artist clicks a button,
and from then on out,

00:33:03.880 --> 00:33:06.680
the editor gets a signal saying
it's ready to be brought in.

00:33:06.730 --> 00:33:08.270
No one has to touch anything.

00:33:08.370 --> 00:33:09.380
It's a very smooth system.

00:33:09.380 --> 00:33:11.690
We're using Cube, XN, NFS.

00:33:11.780 --> 00:33:12.960
It's all very slick.

00:33:13.040 --> 00:33:15.930
We're using, in fact,
Shake to convert every single individual

00:33:16.090 --> 00:33:18.060
frame into a QuickTime movie for import.

00:33:18.140 --> 00:33:21.290
So for those of you who like
Shake can say that Shake is used

00:33:21.450 --> 00:33:23.140
on every shot in South Park.

00:33:24.030 --> 00:33:25.940
After that,
it goes to the editing bay where

00:33:25.940 --> 00:33:29.240
Trey will actually sit down and
edit every part of every show.

00:33:29.240 --> 00:33:31.900
He's very directly involved
in the entire process.

00:33:31.900 --> 00:33:34.310
The retake process, as I mentioned,
we go through.

00:33:34.310 --> 00:33:35.830
It's a very iterative process.

00:33:35.890 --> 00:33:36.900
If Trey likes something, he's great.

00:33:36.900 --> 00:33:38.870
If he doesn't, he'll make notes.

00:33:38.960 --> 00:33:41.340
There have been times where a shot
will come through that completely

00:33:41.370 --> 00:33:42.900
changes where he's going with the show.

00:33:43.010 --> 00:33:45.400
Just because of one little
extra thing an animator did,

00:33:45.480 --> 00:33:47.900
it completely inspires
him in another direction.

00:33:48.060 --> 00:33:50.050
After we finish all of that,
we get video locked,

00:33:50.050 --> 00:33:51.900
which means no more animation is done.

00:33:51.900 --> 00:33:55.640
That's usually around 7:00 or 8:00 AM,
Wednesday, the day it airs.

00:33:57.320 --> 00:33:59.490
After we get video lock,
audio still has another

00:33:59.490 --> 00:34:03.000
couple hours synchronizing
audio to the final animation.

00:34:03.110 --> 00:34:05.230
Once all that's done,
we then roll off the videotape,

00:34:05.340 --> 00:34:08.150
take it for color correction,
and then upload it from Comedy Central's

00:34:08.190 --> 00:34:12.040
Los Angeles office to the
New York office where they broadcast it.

00:34:12.170 --> 00:34:14.970
That usually happens about an hour,
hour and a half before

00:34:15.110 --> 00:34:16.070
it goes on the air.

00:34:17.050 --> 00:34:19.540
Now, on very rare occasion,
if everyone's really kicking

00:34:19.540 --> 00:34:23.070
butt and we're all doing great,
there's tenth stage we reach.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:32.760
Okay, so this is how we do it.

00:34:32.760 --> 00:34:34.040
This is what we use.

00:34:34.040 --> 00:34:35.560
We use all the standard protocols.

00:34:35.560 --> 00:34:39.990
We have servers dedicated
for every individual job.

00:34:40.020 --> 00:34:43.460
We have a server dedicated just
to serving data to the artists.

00:34:43.560 --> 00:34:45.500
Another one just serving
data to the render farm.

00:34:45.500 --> 00:34:48.990
Another one is just dedicated to
converting those frames to QuickTimes.

00:34:48.990 --> 00:34:51.000
We have another one
dedicated just doing backup.

00:34:52.140 --> 00:34:54.000
You can see all the tools we use.

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:57.600
And from the entire staff
and crew of South Park,

00:34:57.600 --> 00:35:00.170
I'd like to thank all you developers
for making those tools and

00:35:00.180 --> 00:35:01.910
enabling us to make the show we do.

00:35:01.950 --> 00:35:04.000
Thank you.

00:35:13.320 --> 00:35:15.160
Thanks a lot.

00:35:15.200 --> 00:35:20.800
Okay,
finally we have Apple in the laboratory,

00:35:20.800 --> 00:35:21.700
Apple in science.

00:35:21.700 --> 00:35:28.560
And this is a great example of a
challenge which is to build a very

00:35:28.560 --> 00:35:33.440
highly collaborative environment
and to leverage open source.

00:35:33.440 --> 00:35:38.790
In the sciences, Mac has actually taken
off in the last few years.

00:35:38.850 --> 00:35:43.880
Part of that is due to the interest in
visualization and of course the great job

00:35:43.880 --> 00:35:46.620
we do at providing visualization tools.

00:35:46.640 --> 00:35:51.590
And the Cinema HD display
has helped a lot there.

00:35:51.670 --> 00:35:56.040
As well as groundbreaking
applications from third parties,

00:35:56.130 --> 00:35:57.280
but also open source.

00:35:57.280 --> 00:36:01.460
Especially in the bioinformatics
field where most of the applications

00:36:01.510 --> 00:36:05.840
that are used in that field were
written in the era of open source.

00:36:05.840 --> 00:36:08.430
That means in the 1990s or later.

00:36:08.470 --> 00:36:12.440
And so what this has led to is a
great amount of sharing in that

00:36:12.440 --> 00:36:17.640
community between researchers,
both commercial researchers as well

00:36:17.640 --> 00:36:20.920
as researchers at institutions.

00:36:20.920 --> 00:36:26.330
StructureBiologyGrid.org,
I think associated with

00:36:26.330 --> 00:36:30.520
the Harvard Medical School,
but actually a distributed

00:36:30.550 --> 00:36:35.640
collaborative environment is
going to be talked about by Dr.

00:36:35.640 --> 00:36:38.770
David Goharra from
Washington University School of

00:36:38.770 --> 00:36:41.360
Medicine Center for
Computational Biology.

00:36:41.360 --> 00:36:43.690
So, David.

00:36:48.380 --> 00:36:50.590
Thank you, Bud.

00:36:50.660 --> 00:36:53.640
It's really a great pleasure to be
here today and for the opportunity

00:36:53.640 --> 00:36:55.650
to be able to share with you some
of the work that we've been doing

00:36:56.090 --> 00:36:59.210
and some of the ways that we've
integrated Apple technology in the lab.

00:36:59.370 --> 00:37:01.740
But before I do that,
I'd like to give you a little bit

00:37:01.740 --> 00:37:04.810
of background about SB Grid and
some of the things that we do.

00:37:04.920 --> 00:37:06.830
SBGrid started in the
lab of Steve Harrison at

00:37:06.830 --> 00:37:11.580
Harvard Medical School out of a
need to unify and standardize the

00:37:11.580 --> 00:37:15.010
software and computing environments
that his lab members were using,

00:37:15.140 --> 00:37:17.660
with a specific focus on
x-ray crystallography,

00:37:17.660 --> 00:37:19.900
electron microscopy, and NMR.

00:37:19.900 --> 00:37:24.980
My primary responsibility as part
of SBGrid is to identify performance

00:37:24.980 --> 00:37:29.680
bottlenecks in our users' calculations
and then to develop solutions to help

00:37:29.680 --> 00:37:31.900
them get those calculations done faster.

00:37:32.110 --> 00:37:34.380
Since its inception,
SBGrid has expanded to 14 other

00:37:34.380 --> 00:37:39.000
institutions across the country,
and we now have over 50 labs and

00:37:39.030 --> 00:37:43.680
support over 500 users with software.

00:37:44.680 --> 00:37:47.250
Almost all of the applications we
use are open source software and

00:37:47.310 --> 00:37:48.770
can be run from the command line.

00:37:48.770 --> 00:37:51.600
And so any system we use has
to provide a UNIX environment.

00:37:51.600 --> 00:37:54.600
And because we're dealing
with open source applications,

00:37:54.600 --> 00:37:56.580
we need developer tools
and performance tools.

00:37:56.590 --> 00:37:59.600
We need everything that's
required for porting,

00:37:59.600 --> 00:38:02.600
building,
and optimizing open source applications.

00:38:02.600 --> 00:38:06.190
As structural biologists,
molecular visualization is very,

00:38:06.190 --> 00:38:07.520
very important to us.

00:38:07.590 --> 00:38:10.600
We want to be able to relate
structure to function,

00:38:10.600 --> 00:38:14.600
and so we need to see what's going
on with large molecular assemblies.

00:38:14.600 --> 00:38:17.820
And so having access to
high definition displays,

00:38:17.820 --> 00:38:20.970
fast graphics cards,
and stereo graphics hardware

00:38:21.260 --> 00:38:25.170
is not only important for us,
it's an absolute requirement.

00:38:25.600 --> 00:38:28.760
We typically tend to turn
over or upgrade our hardware

00:38:28.760 --> 00:38:30.900
faster than we decommission it.

00:38:30.900 --> 00:38:34.560
And so anytime we bring new
system types into the mix,

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:37.700
they have to be able to work well
in a mixed computing environment.

00:38:37.700 --> 00:38:40.260
So interoperability is really key.

00:38:40.260 --> 00:38:43.250
But probably the most important thing
for us is the fact that the types

00:38:43.250 --> 00:38:46.550
of problems that we deal with are
extremely computationally expensive.

00:38:46.560 --> 00:38:52.310
I'm going to give you an
example of that in a little bit.

00:38:53.460 --> 00:38:57.980
What's really key to us is the fact that
we need systems that are priced well,

00:38:58.130 --> 00:39:00.400
that are fast, and that are reliable.

00:39:00.400 --> 00:39:04.630
And so what we really strive to do is
we want to minimize the bottlenecks that

00:39:04.630 --> 00:39:07.850
are introduced by the calculation itself,
and have the science and the

00:39:07.850 --> 00:39:10.830
understanding of that science
be the rate-limiting step

00:39:10.860 --> 00:39:12.210
in everything that we do.

00:39:12.400 --> 00:39:15.480
And so having systems that
ship with multiple CPUs,

00:39:15.480 --> 00:39:17.870
vector units,
and highly tuned vector numeric

00:39:17.870 --> 00:39:23.400
libraries that we can use out of the
box are very important features for us.

00:39:24.730 --> 00:39:28.010
Our first entry into high-performance
computing solutions from Apple was

00:39:28.010 --> 00:39:30.200
a 14-node XSERV G5 cluster.

00:39:30.200 --> 00:39:33.340
And that system was commissioned
primarily for some of the EM work that

00:39:33.340 --> 00:39:35.320
was being done in the Harvard labs.

00:39:35.450 --> 00:39:39.860
On the desktop, we're using primarily
Power Mac G5s and iMac G5s.

00:39:39.870 --> 00:39:42.520
We've seen some of the
Intel Macs coming in as well.

00:39:42.620 --> 00:39:44.630
And in terms of our
graphics workstations,

00:39:44.640 --> 00:39:48.760
we're still using the Power Mac G5s,
now with dual LCD displays.

00:39:48.890 --> 00:39:53.640
And in the case of stereo graphics,
we'll attach CRT monitors to those.

00:39:53.640 --> 00:39:57.640
So let me give you just one quick example
of how we've used the technologies that

00:39:57.640 --> 00:40:04.400
ship with these systems to be able to
speed up some of our users' calculations.

00:40:04.590 --> 00:40:06.900
We had a user that was performing
a calculation that would take

00:40:06.900 --> 00:40:08.100
about 10 days per iteration.

00:40:08.100 --> 00:40:09.790
And at the end of that,
he'd sit in front of the

00:40:09.790 --> 00:40:12.440
graphics workstation,
move some things around,

00:40:12.440 --> 00:40:14.550
analyze the results, of course.

00:40:14.590 --> 00:40:16.990
That's what we were
referred to as analyzing it.

00:40:17.060 --> 00:40:19.470
And then he'd resubmit
it for calculation again.

00:40:19.740 --> 00:40:22.100
And so what this really meant was
that he was spending about three

00:40:22.100 --> 00:40:25.340
days out of the month on this
actual portion of the project,

00:40:25.380 --> 00:40:28.750
and the rest of the time he
was simply waiting for results.

00:40:29.650 --> 00:40:33.700
And so the performance tools that
are provided with Xcode Shark told

00:40:33.700 --> 00:40:36.160
us immediately that we're spending,
with this particular application,

00:40:36.160 --> 00:40:39.340
we're spending about 30% of our time
allocating and deallocating memory.

00:40:39.340 --> 00:40:43.400
And that this memory allocation turned
out to just simply be for scratch space.

00:40:43.400 --> 00:40:47.320
And so we could move that allocation to
the beginning of the program's execution,

00:40:47.320 --> 00:40:50.010
and we could immediately get the
runtime down to about seven days.

00:40:51.190 --> 00:40:53.060
Continuing on,
we could see that the program

00:40:53.060 --> 00:40:54.520
was doing a lot of two things.

00:40:54.540 --> 00:40:57.530
It was moving data around,
it was transposing it,

00:40:57.540 --> 00:41:01.040
three-dimensional data set,
and it was calculating a lot of FFTs.

00:41:01.040 --> 00:41:03.600
And if you're on a Mac and you want
to do either one of those two things,

00:41:03.600 --> 00:41:06.350
the first place you really want to
look is the Accelerate framework.

00:41:06.470 --> 00:41:12.620
Some of the fastest FFTs available
anywhere are in Accelerate.

00:41:12.730 --> 00:41:15.800
And so after integrating Accelerate,
we were able to get the

00:41:15.800 --> 00:41:18.330
runtime down to about 5.6 days.

00:41:18.580 --> 00:41:20.550
And so then continuing on,
what we could see was that the

00:41:20.550 --> 00:41:24.580
application was doing a lot of similar
operations on these large chunks of data,

00:41:24.700 --> 00:41:27.450
and that the operations that
were occurring over here could

00:41:27.450 --> 00:41:29.950
be done independent of the
operations that were over here.

00:41:30.100 --> 00:41:32.300
And so then after
multi-threading the application,

00:41:32.300 --> 00:41:34.650
we could get the runtime
down to about 3.7 days.

00:41:34.730 --> 00:41:36.900
And so at this point, I say, "Okay, hey,
that's not bad.

00:41:36.900 --> 00:41:39.850
Take it back to the user and to the
user's boss." And the user's boss

00:41:39.850 --> 00:41:41.090
happened to actually be my boss.

00:41:41.300 --> 00:41:44.260
And the user's boss, who was my boss,
was happy, and so the user was happy,

00:41:44.290 --> 00:41:45.100
and so I was happy.

00:41:45.300 --> 00:41:46.500
Great.

00:41:46.500 --> 00:41:51.500
And so normally we just sort of leave
it there and move on to something else,

00:41:51.500 --> 00:41:52.900
but we didn't.

00:41:52.900 --> 00:41:54.780
In fact,
the story gets a little bit better

00:41:54.940 --> 00:41:59.400
because what I realized is that in
thinking about the problem a bit more,

00:41:59.400 --> 00:42:02.830
the particular calculation that
this user was doing was inherently

00:42:02.830 --> 00:42:07.300
a parallel calculation that was
masquerading itself as a serial one.

00:42:07.300 --> 00:42:10.370
And so we backed off on
the multi-threading code,

00:42:10.410 --> 00:42:15.400
and instead I wrote a Cocoa app that
would break the job up into chunks,

00:42:15.400 --> 00:42:17.860
send it off to XGrid,
and then XGrid could farm it out.

00:42:17.970 --> 00:42:21.040
And so what we ended up with
is a calculation that was

00:42:21.040 --> 00:42:25.300
taking 5.6 days on one CPU and
originally 10 days on one CPU.

00:42:25.300 --> 00:42:29.500
We could farm it out to 26 CPUs and
get the calculation down to 0.2 days,

00:42:29.500 --> 00:42:31.300
or roughly about five hours.

00:42:31.300 --> 00:42:34.380
And so what this meant was that
the user could start the job

00:42:34.380 --> 00:42:37.700
in the evening before he left,
and when he got back in in the morning,

00:42:37.700 --> 00:42:39.590
the results were now waiting for him.

00:42:39.640 --> 00:42:40.880
So it was a complete opposite.

00:42:41.050 --> 00:42:43.630
And this is just one example of how
we've been able to take advantage

00:42:43.630 --> 00:42:46.570
of some of the technologies that
ship with Apple hardware and

00:42:46.570 --> 00:42:50.300
software to really get some great
performance out of our applications.

00:42:50.300 --> 00:42:55.280
