We now support SATA and SAS drives.

00:47:33.070 --> 00:47:39.200
So you can actually get tremendous
performance with the drives built in.

00:47:39.200 --> 00:47:43.980
As you can see, scientific benchmarks,
LINPACK is used.

00:47:44.250 --> 00:47:47.300
To demonstrate the
overall system throughput.

00:47:47.500 --> 00:47:52.970
So you have tremendous memory system,
processor, and disk performance

00:47:53.080 --> 00:47:56.700
that lead up to a very,
very good LINPACK result.

00:47:56.710 --> 00:48:01.270
Almost three times faster in
double precision and 3.2 times

00:48:01.400 --> 00:48:03.450
faster in single precision.

00:48:04.120 --> 00:48:09.300
Super fast memory back set up,
fully buffered DIMMs, 2x the capacity,

00:48:09.300 --> 00:48:14.390
32GB in a single 1U system,
increased high availability features

00:48:14.390 --> 00:48:18.150
to keep these things up and running,
ECC with on-demand scrubbing,

00:48:18.160 --> 00:48:21.420
CRC protection of the data,
so the transactions between the

00:48:21.420 --> 00:48:23.990
memory DIMMs and the systems
are protected with CRCs,

00:48:24.080 --> 00:48:30.650
giving the system the ability
to recover from transient errors

00:48:30.650 --> 00:48:30.810
rather than coming to a halt.

00:48:31.480 --> 00:48:33.540
There's massive memory
bandwidth in this machine,

00:48:33.600 --> 00:48:36.620
2.1 times more than
the original XServe G5.

