Tremendously flexible storage.

00:48:42.900 --> 00:48:46.830
The SATA, of course, is no small feat.

00:48:47.130 --> 00:48:52.390
2.25 terabytes of internal hot-plug
storage in this 1U machine.

00:48:52.960 --> 00:48:56.240
24x7 server rated drives,
very very important.

00:48:56.240 --> 00:48:59.460
And of course, if you want really
really high performance,

00:48:59.460 --> 00:49:03.960
with the SAS drives you
get 125 MB/s per drive,

00:49:03.960 --> 00:49:05.420
3.5 ms of seek.

00:49:05.770 --> 00:49:09.090
These are ideal for large
database applications,

00:49:09.090 --> 00:49:13.020
anything that really has very
very I/O intense operation.

00:49:13.720 --> 00:49:16.730
As you can see,
this is just comparing SATA and

00:49:16.810 --> 00:49:18.240
SAS in the same machine.

00:49:18.290 --> 00:49:21.400
Both of them are quite fast,
but the SAS is really unbelievable.

00:49:21.400 --> 00:49:22.840
125 megabytes a second.

00:49:22.840 --> 00:49:26.340
Remember, you have three of those drives,
so you actually have three times

00:49:26.340 --> 00:49:29.180
that bandwidth if you stripe them.

00:49:29.620 --> 00:49:33.560
And the seek time means that
for large data sets with random

00:49:33.640 --> 00:49:36.810
access behavior like a database,
you have tremendously high

00:49:36.820 --> 00:49:38.970
performance right in the box.

00:49:39.600 --> 00:49:41.300
And then of course the I/O.

00:49:41.300 --> 00:49:44.810
We have two, as I said,
two by eight PCI Express card slots.

00:49:44.810 --> 00:49:47.440
One is a standard slot
for 6.8 inch cards,

00:49:47.440 --> 00:49:49.140
so fiber channel cards and the like.

