into a single storage pool.

00:55:05.490 --> 00:55:09.700
It scales up to two petabytes
and it provides uptime through

00:55:09.700 --> 00:55:11.630
redundant metadata controllers.

00:55:11.740 --> 00:55:13.230
So XAN does all this today.

00:55:13.390 --> 00:55:14.010
So what's new?

00:55:14.110 --> 00:55:16.640
Well,
I'm sure you've guessed it's universal.

00:55:16.750 --> 00:55:19.900
So it runs on the new
Mac Pro hardware and AXSERVs and

00:55:19.900 --> 00:55:24.300
you can mix and match Intel and
PowerPC systems on the same SAN.

00:55:24.410 --> 00:55:28.420
And we have one more feature
that's new in XAN 1.4 and that's

00:55:28.420 --> 00:55:30.550
Access Control List support.

00:55:34.110 --> 00:55:37.570
Up till now, XAN has been limited by
Unix access privileges,

00:55:37.570 --> 00:55:41.200
and that's fairly difficult to map into
your workflows in your shared workgroups,

00:55:41.260 --> 00:55:42.700
especially in video workgroups.

00:55:42.760 --> 00:55:45.620
And so we've removed that limitation,
and it's now fully compatible

00:55:45.620 --> 00:55:47.130
with Tiger Access Control List.

00:55:47.180 --> 00:55:51.120
So you can map it to your workflow
and not have to map your workflow

00:55:51.230 --> 00:55:53.300
into your access privileges.

00:55:53.400 --> 00:55:58.160
So XAN 1.4 has also made
the transition to Intel.

00:55:58.700 --> 00:56:02.640
So our biggest release today that
we're working on now is Leopard Server.

00:56:02.650 --> 00:56:05.670
This is going to be shipping
in the spring of 2007,

00:56:05.670 --> 00:56:07.640
and we have a lot of new features coming.

00:56:07.790 --> 00:56:09.730
So here's just a few.

00:56:09.810 --> 00:56:11.420
The first is the iCal Server.

00:56:11.660 --> 00:56:14.850
This is a complete calendaring server.

00:56:19.200 --> 00:56:22.700
And it's got everything that you'd expect
from a full-fledged calendaring server.

00:56:22.830 --> 00:56:25.660
So,
users can schedule events and meetings,

00:56:25.760 --> 00:56:30.790
you can send invitations, receive them,
you can search free busy time, proxies,

00:56:30.850 --> 00:56:33.200
access control,
all the features you'd expect.

00:56:33.200 --> 00:56:37.460
And the most important feature is
that it's built on an open standard,

00:56:37.460 --> 00:56:38.200
CalDAV.

00:56:38.200 --> 00:56:41.200
So it not only works with
the iCal client in Leopard,

00:56:41.200 --> 00:56:46.200
but it also works with other clients such
as Mozilla's Sunbird or OSAF's Chandler.

00:56:47.200 --> 00:56:50.200
We've designed it from the
ground up to be scalable.

00:56:50.200 --> 00:56:53.640
So you can start simple with
one server and then grow as you

00:56:53.640 --> 00:56:57.200
need to with multiple servers
all sharing the same calendaring

00:56:57.200 --> 00:56:59.200
database on the back end with XAN.

00:56:59.200 --> 00:57:01.830
And because we want to
promote the adoption of this

00:57:01.840 --> 00:57:04.580
server as well as CalDAV,
we're actually releasing

00:57:04.580 --> 00:57:08.790
the complete open source,
the complete source to the server as open

00:57:08.790 --> 00:57:12.580
source as the Darwin Calendar Server and
that will be available this

00:57:12.650 --> 00:57:14.200
week under the Apache license.

00:57:21.810 --> 00:57:25.290
So another new service
in Leopard is Teams.

00:57:25.480 --> 00:57:29.670
Teams is a wiki and a set of web
services that easily allows groups

00:57:30.020 --> 00:57:33.700
or project teams to create and share
information using Leopard's server.

00:57:33.700 --> 00:57:36.940
We use wikis a lot inside of
Apple and they're really powerful,

00:57:36.940 --> 00:57:41.210
but sometimes the usage model can
be really arcane and some of the

00:57:41.210 --> 00:57:42.700
markup language is hard to use.

00:57:42.700 --> 00:57:44.690
We've solved all that in Teams.

00:57:44.870 --> 00:57:45.700
Teams uses Ajax.

00:57:45.700 --> 00:57:48.700
It's all truly what you
see is what you get.

00:57:48.700 --> 00:57:49.920
It's direct editing.

00:57:49.920 --> 00:57:52.700
If you can use a word processor,
you can use Teams.

00:57:52.790 --> 00:57:53.720
And so Teams is new.

00:57:53.720 --> 00:57:55.900
It's a wiki service in Leopard's server.

00:57:55.900 --> 00:57:57.700
And it's more than just that.

00:57:57.700 --> 00:57:59.620
It also has a lot of
other services as well.

00:57:59.740 --> 00:58:01.610
So there's shared group calendars.

00:58:01.700 --> 00:58:04.680
You can publish information
through blogs and podcasts.

00:58:04.710 --> 00:58:08.860
So it's truly a rich set of services
for Teams to create and share content

00:58:09.070 --> 00:58:11.700
using Leopard's server through the web.

00:58:11.700 --> 00:58:16.670
Now both Teams and iCal
Server actually use open directory.

00:58:16.710 --> 00:58:17.700
They're actually integrated there.

00:58:17.700 --> 00:58:22.700
So all of the information they need,
such as groups and shared contacts,

00:58:22.700 --> 00:58:26.810
resources, rooms, locations,
other things like that,

00:58:26.810 --> 00:58:28.660
are all now stored in open directory.

00:58:28.760 --> 00:58:31.770
And so we've introduced another
application as well called the

00:58:31.770 --> 00:58:35.010
Teams directory that actually lets
normal users who need to work with

00:58:35.110 --> 00:58:37.700
these entries create and manage these.

00:58:37.700 --> 00:58:39.700
So you can create
project teams or groups.

00:58:39.700 --> 00:58:42.700
You can manage their membership,
rooms and locations,

00:58:42.700 --> 00:58:44.700
resources that are used by iCal.

00:58:44.700 --> 00:58:46.700
All of these can be created
using Teams directory.

00:58:46.700 --> 00:58:48.930
using Teams directory.

00:58:50.650 --> 00:58:53.760
Another new feature in Leopard
Server is streamlined setup.

00:58:53.820 --> 00:58:55.840
Tiger Server was already
very easy to set up,

00:58:55.840 --> 00:58:57.010
and we've made it even simpler.

00:58:57.120 --> 00:58:59.600
So it's very quick to get
the server up and running.

00:58:59.830 --> 00:59:02.600
But also, it's not just the server,
it's also the clients as well.

00:59:02.600 --> 00:59:05.360
We've automated the client setup,
so all your applications in the

00:59:05.360 --> 00:59:09.190
client that work with the server,
such as mail, chat, calendaring,

00:59:09.190 --> 00:59:12.510
time machine, etc., can all be easily
configured to work with the

00:59:12.510 --> 00:59:14.060
server in just a few clicks.

00:59:14.060 --> 00:59:16.730
So if you need to set up a server
with a collection of clients,

00:59:16.730 --> 00:59:19.450
it's very easy, very quick,
and there's truly no day-to-day

00:59:19.450 --> 00:59:20.580
management that goes into it.

00:59:20.600 --> 00:59:23.900
And in addition, as part of our server
management enhancements,

00:59:23.900 --> 00:59:25.640
we've also integrated backup.

00:59:25.640 --> 00:59:28.530
So now the server uses time
machine to backup your server

00:59:28.610 --> 00:59:30.160
settings and data as well.

00:59:33.080 --> 00:59:36.990
Spotlight Server allows you to easily
search for content both locally

00:59:37.090 --> 00:59:39.200
and now on your server as well.

00:59:39.240 --> 00:59:41.980
So in Leopard,
when you do a Spotlight search,

00:59:42.040 --> 00:59:46.000
it will transparently search for all the
content on your mounted server volumes.

00:59:46.170 --> 00:59:49.660
There's no configuration required
and it'll support all the features,

00:59:49.660 --> 00:59:53.000
the new features of Spotlight
such as advanced search queries.

00:59:53.000 --> 00:59:54.840
On the server,
everything happens automatically.

00:59:54.840 --> 00:59:56.000
You don't need to configure it.

00:59:56.000 --> 00:59:58.880
The indexing happens automatically
for all your content.

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:02.370
It's done in the background at a lower
priority so it doesn't interfere with

01:00:02.380 --> 01:00:04.000
the performance of your services.

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:07.300
And of course, as you would expect,
it adheres to the file access

01:00:07.300 --> 01:00:10.100
privileges so people only see
the results for the files that

01:00:10.190 --> 01:00:12.000
they're actually allowed to access.

01:00:13.610 --> 01:00:16.160
We have another new service
called Podcast Producer.

01:00:16.270 --> 01:00:19.400
Podcast Producer is an end-to-end
solution for capturing,

01:00:19.400 --> 01:00:22.500
encoding, and publishing content
on the web as a podcast.

01:00:22.500 --> 01:00:27.380
It's great for people who quickly and
easily need to be able to capture audio

01:00:27.380 --> 01:00:30.010
or video feeds and publish them out.

01:00:30.200 --> 01:00:33.550
You can set up an automatic workflow
so that you can capture video or

01:00:33.550 --> 01:00:35.710
audio content on a Leopard client.

01:00:35.710 --> 01:00:39.460
It's automatically uploaded to the server
where it can be encoded in any number

01:00:39.460 --> 01:00:42.560
of formats that QuickTime supports.

01:00:42.560 --> 01:00:46.760
And then it's published out to
the web as a podcast via RSS.

01:00:46.910 --> 01:00:49.490
It's integrated with Open Directory to
control who can publish

01:00:49.840 --> 01:00:51.300
content through your services.

01:00:51.300 --> 01:00:54.500
And all the encoding is
hosted on top of XGrid.

01:00:54.500 --> 01:00:57.050
So you can start with a single server,
but then you can grow as

01:00:57.050 --> 01:00:58.260
your encoding needs grow.

01:00:58.260 --> 01:01:04.060
So it's a great end-to-end solution
for rapidly capturing content

01:01:04.060 --> 01:01:06.560
and getting it out to the web.

01:01:13.330 --> 01:01:18.100
So the iCal Server, Teams Wiki,
Spotlight Server, Podcast Producer,

01:01:18.100 --> 01:01:21.510
these are a few of the major
new services in Leopard Server.

01:01:21.510 --> 01:01:23.300
There's a whole bunch more.

01:01:23.300 --> 01:01:26.110
We have clustering in the mail services.

01:01:26.490 --> 01:01:30.840
We have a federation of instant
messaging servers with iChat Server 2.

01:01:30.840 --> 01:01:34.930
We have the ability to host
distributed computing without a

01:01:34.930 --> 01:01:36.600
dedicated controller in XSquare 2.

01:01:36.600 --> 01:01:39.710
As well as in the CoreOS foundations,
we have the ability to

01:01:39.710 --> 01:01:43.270
perform 64-bit computing now
at all layers of the system.

01:01:43.300 --> 01:01:46.960
So there's a lot of stuff that's new.

